            <fr:title text="Finish constructing mutliplication of Dedekind cuts, and it forms an ordered field">Finish constructing mutliplication of Dedekind cuts, and it forms an ordered field</fr:title>
            <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/baby-rudin/" title="Principles of Mathematical Analysis" uri="http://localhost:8000/baby-rudin/" display-uri="baby-rudin" type="local">Principles of Mathematical Analysis</fr:link>, Appendix to Ch. 1</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>We then define the multiplication for <html:em>any arbitrary</html:em> <fr:link href="/ca-000U/" title="Dedekind cuts" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-000U/" display-uri="ca-000U" type="local">Dedekind cuts</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in  R]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \in  R]]></fr:tex> by
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\alpha \beta  = \begin {cases}(-\alpha )(-\beta ) & \hbox {if }\alpha <0_{R},\beta <0_{R},\\
-[(-\alpha )\beta ] & \hbox {if }\alpha <0_{R}<\beta \\
-[\alpha \cdot (-\beta )] & \hbox {if }\beta <0_{R}<\alpha .
\end {cases}]]></fr:tex>
The product used in each of these cases is the one from <fr:link href="/ca-000Y/" title="Addition of Dedekind cuts satisfies the relevant ordered field axioms" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-000Y/" display-uri="ca-000Y" type="local">Addition of Dedekind cuts satisfies the relevant ordered field axioms</fr:link>.</html:p>
            <html:p>Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma =-(-\gamma )]]></fr:tex>, the axioms for multiplication of a <fr:link href="/field-0001/" title="Field" uri="http://localhost:8000/field-0001/" display-uri="field-0001" type="local">Field</fr:link> holds for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> except we need to check distributivity.</html:p>
            <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ,\beta ,\gamma \in  R]]></fr:tex>. Then
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\alpha (\beta +\gamma )=\alpha \beta +\alpha \gamma .]]></fr:tex>
The proof breaks up into cases depending on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha >0_{R}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha <0_{R}]]></fr:tex>, and separately <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta >0_{R}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta <0_{R}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta +\gamma >0_{R}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta +\gamma <0_{R}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>For example, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha >0_{R}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta <0_{R}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta +\gamma >0_{R}]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\gamma =(\beta +\gamma )+(-\beta )]]></fr:tex>, which means
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\alpha \gamma =\alpha (\beta +\gamma )+\alpha \cdot (-\beta )]]></fr:tex>
But <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \cdot (-\beta )=-(\alpha \beta )]]></fr:tex>. Thus
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\alpha \beta +\alpha \gamma =\alpha (\beta +\gamma ).]]></fr:tex>
The remaining cases are proved similarly.</html:p>
